				 More funds to support spend
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT				 	 Chidambaram: Cash chase																								New Delhi, Nov. 20: Finance minister P. Chidambaram has asked for additional gross expenditure of Rs 33,290 crore till March 2008. 																								Of the total amount, the net cash outgo will be Rs 11,869.60 crore and gross additional expenditure will be Rs 21,420.82 crore.																								The finance minister tabled the supplementary demands for grants in the Lok Sabha today.																								The grant will partly compensate oil marketing firms, which are selling fuels at subsidised rates. Chidambaram has asked for Rs 11,256.92 crore to meet the oil bond commitment.																								Last month, the cabinet approved bonds worth Rs 23,457 crore to oil marketing companies in 2007-08, which would cover 42.7 per cent of their projected revenue loss.																								Other major expenditures listed by the minister were Rs 4,500 crore for interest liabilities under the market stabilisation scheme and Rs 4,763.28 crore to write off loans to state governments under debt waiver schemes under the 12th Finance Commission Award.																								The government will also spend Rs 900 crore on tax refunds and interest subsidies for exporters. 
